statement.p:
Suppose that A is the matrix

					A = \mat{
					2 1;
					6 5;
					2 4
					}



Explain in words how knowing all solutions to Ax=b decides if a given vector b is in the column space of A.

Is the vector b=\vec{8 28 14} in the column space of A?

ol.li:
Yes. Reducing the matrix combining A and b gives

							\amat{
							2 1 8;
							6 5 28;
							2 4 14
							}
							\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
							\amat{
							2 1 8;
							0 2 4;
							0 3 6
							}
							\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
							\amat{
							2 1 8;
							0 2 4;
							0 0 0
							}

						Thus, x=\vec{3 2} is a solution to Ax=b, and b is in the column space of A.

statement.p:
Suppose A is the matrix

					A=\mat{
					0 1 2 2;
					0 3 8 7;
					0 0 4 2
					}



Find all special solutions to Ax=0 and describe in words the whole nullspace of A.

Describe the column space of A. All combinations of four columns is not a sufficient answer.

ol.li:
First, by row reduction


								\mat{
								0 1 2 2;
								0 3 8 7;
								0 0 4 2
								}
								\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
								\mat{
								0 1 2 2;
								0 0 2 1;
								0 0 4 2
								}
								\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
								\mat{
								0 1 0 1;
								0 0 2 1;
								0 0 0 0
								}


								\quad\xrightarrow{}\quad
								\mat{
								0 1 0 1;
								0 0 1 \frac{1}{2};
								0 0 0 0
								}



						so the special solutions are s_1=\vec{1 0 0 0}, s_2=\vec{0 -1 -\frac{1}{2} 1}. Thus \Nul(A) is a plane in \R^4 given by all linear combinations of the special solutions.
